She also denied claims that the duo was in crowded cells and might, therefore, have suffocated to death.
Post-mortem report 
However, a post-mortem report revealed that the suspects may have died of injuries inflicted at the police station or lack of sufficient oxygen due to congestion.
Government Chief Pathologist Dr Johansen Oduor disapproved of the theory by the police that Covid-19 claimed the lives of the victims.
According to Dr Oduor, who performed the autopsy at Kerugoya Referral Hospital mortuary, both victims had internal head and stomach injuries and lacked enough oxygen.
Following the post-mortem, families of the two villagers are now crying for justice.
Meanwhile, Kiambaa MP Paul Koinange, who is also the National Assembly Committee on Administration and Security chairman, has vowed to raise the matter with Interior Cabinet Secretary Dr Fred Matiang'i.
The committee chairman expressed concern over the deplorable state of Wang'uru police station in Kirinyaga County where the two remandees were locked up before their death.
He described the police station as unsafe and dangerous for both officers and remandees.
Mr Koinange sad the station, which was built in 1957 during the colonial era, was congested and needed to be expanded.



